<p>Oklahoma's solar resource potential is among the strongest in the United States, with the state receiving an average of 5.1 peak sun hours per day annually. This solar irradiance translates to approximately 1,860 kWh of annual production per installed kW of solar capacity under optimal conditions. The state's location in the south-central United States provides consistent solar exposure throughout the year, with peak production months from April through September coinciding perfectly with high air conditioning demands. Oklahoma's relatively clear skies and low precipitation during summer months ensure minimal interference with solar panel performance during peak production periods.</p>

<p>The seasonal variation in solar production across Oklahoma is relatively moderate, with summer months producing approximately 30-40% more electricity than winter months. This production pattern aligns well with residential energy consumption patterns, as air conditioning loads create the highest electricity bills during the same period when solar panels produce the most energy. A typical 6kW residential solar system in Oklahoma can generate between 8,500-11,500 kWh annually, depending on roof orientation, shading, and specific location within the state. South-facing installations with minimal shading can achieve capacity factors of 18-22%, which compares favorably to national averages.</p>

<p>Geographic variations within Oklahoma show slightly higher solar resource potential in the western and southwestern regions of the state, though the differences are minimal for residential applications. Cities like Oklahoma City, Tulsa, Norman, and Lawton all receive excellent solar resource levels that support strong economic returns on solar investments. The state's relatively flat terrain and minimal air pollution contribute to consistent solar panel performance, while the continental climate provides the temperature variations that help optimize photovoltaic efficiency during cooler months.</p>

