<h2>HVAC Systems in Oklahoma</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>

<p>Oklahoma's continental climate presents unique challenges and opportunities for HVAC system design and operation. The state experiences hot, humid summers with average high temperatures reaching 92-95¬∞F in July and August, combined with humidity levels that often exceed 60-70%. These conditions create substantial cooling loads that require robust air conditioning systems capable of handling both sensible and latent heat removal. Summer cooling degree days typically range from 1,800-2,400 annually, indicating significant air conditioning demands that drive the majority of residential energy consumption during peak months.</p>

<p>Winter heating requirements in Oklahoma are moderate, with average low temperatures ranging from 25-35¬∞F during December and January. Heating degree days average 3,000-3,800 annually, suggesting that while heating is necessary, the loads are manageable and much lower than cooling requirements. This climate pattern makes heat pump systems particularly attractive in Oklahoma, as they can provide efficient heating during mild winter conditions while offering excellent cooling performance during the demanding summer months. The shoulder seasons of spring and fall provide opportunities for natural ventilation and reduced HVAC loads, extending equipment life and reducing annual operating costs.</p>

<p>Oklahoma's climate also includes periodic extreme weather events, including ice storms, severe thunderstorms, and occasional tornadoes. These conditions require HVAC systems to be robust and reliable, with proper installation and maintenance being critical for long-term performance. The state's variable weather patterns also benefit from programmable thermostats and zoned systems that can adapt to changing conditions and occupancy patterns, maximizing comfort while minimizing energy consumption.</p>

